utrius horum, etc.: the poet puts the alternative directly, whether a man should scorn the advantages of intercourse with the great, like the Cynic, or make the most of them, like the versatile Aristippus.

16. doce, etc.: i.e. either con· vince me, or else, being younger, listen to my decision of the point.

17. namque, etc.= i.e. I say Aristippus’ view is better, for he had a valid reply to the reproach of Diogenes.

18. mordacem: in allusion to the etymology of Cynic from κύων. -- eludebat, parried. The imper-

fect represents that his answer was a possible regular reply to such an argument.

19. scurror, I play the parasite, implying that Diogenes had in effect taunted him with being a scurra.
